n, Lancashire, England":"Euxton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1466–1516":"1466–1516","1478–Female":"1478–Deceased","1505–1552":"1505–1552","1508–1535":"1508–1535","March 1504":"March 1504","1535":"1535","1478":"1478","1466":"1466","1552":"1552","1 Jul 1508":"1 July 1508","1508":"1508","1505":"1505","1516":"1516","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Croston, Lancashire":"Croston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Euxton, Lancashire, England":"Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Anderton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the three places so named, in Cheshire, Lancashire, and Devon. Those in Cheshire and Lancashire are named with the personal name <i>Ēanrēd</i> (Old English) or <i>Eindrithi</i> (Old Norse) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. The Devon placename, recorded as <i>Underdon</i> in 1270, means ‘below the down’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Anderton was born in 1466, in Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. He married Joan in March 1504, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1516, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1466–1516":"1466–1516","1478–Female":"1478–Surnud","1505–1552":"1505–1552","1508–1535":"1508–1535","March 1504":"märts 1504","1535":"1535","1478":"1478","1466":"1466","1552":"1552","1 Jul 1508":"1. juuli 1508","1508":"1508","1505":"1505","1516":"1516","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Croston, Lancashire":"Croston, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Euxton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Euxton, Lancashire, England":"Euxton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1466–1516":"1466–1516","1478–Female":"1478–Kuollut","1505–1552":"1505–1552","1508–1535":"1508–1535","March 1504":"maaliskuu 1504","1535":"1535","1478":"1478","1466":"1466","1552":"1552","1 Jul 1508":"1. heinäkuuta 1508","1508":"1508","1505":"1505","1516":"1516","Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Croston, Lancashire":"Croston, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Euxton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Euxton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Euxton, Lancashire, England":"Euxton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1466–1516":"1466–1516","1478–Female":"1478–Décédée","1505–1552":"1505–1552"